WEBVTT

00:04.258 --> 00:06.161
Welcome to the Gospel and Life podcast.

00:06.782 --> 00:12.292
Many of us often focus on the big moments in Jesus' life, his birth, death, and resurrection.

00:12.933 --> 00:19.444
But how would your understanding of Jesus change if you took a closer look at what he did and said throughout his life on earth?

00:20.285 --> 00:30.322
Today Tim Keller explores why Jesus' everyday experiences are essential for understanding who he is and how they invite us to have a deeper trust in him.

00:38.498 --> 00:43.663
Scripture reading this morning is from John chapter 1, verses 1 through 14.

00:43.683 --> 00:53.213
In the beginning was the Word, and the Word was with God, and the Word was God.

00:54.654 --> 00:56.376
He was with God in the beginning.

00:57.977 --> 01:00.040
Through Him all things were made.

01:01.181 --> 01:03.463
Without Him nothing was made that has been made.

01:04.784 --> 01:06.546
In Him was life.

01:07.682 --> 01:10.246
And that life was the light of all mankind.

01:11.708 --> 01:14.492
The light shines in the darkness.

01:16.015 --> 01:17.757
And the darkness has not overcome it.

01:19.540 --> 01:22.004
There was a man sent from God whose name was John.

01:23.125 --> 01:29.034
He came as a witness to testify concerning that light so that through him all might believe.

01:30.176 --> 01:31.458
He himself was not the light.

01:32.319 --> 01:34.542
He came only as a witness to the light.

01:36.005 --> 01:36.946
The true light

01:37.186 --> 01:39.990
that gives light to everyone was coming into the world.

01:41.433 --> 01:48.203
He was in the world, and though the world was made through him, the world did not recognize him.

01:49.706 --> 01:55.154
He came to that which was his own, but his own did not receive him.

01:56.717 --> 02:05.010
Yet to all who did receive him, to those who believed in his name, he gave the right to become children of God.

02:05.762 --> 02:14.094
Children born not of natural descent, nor of human decision, or a husband's will, but born of God.

02:16.137 --> 02:21.404
The Word became flesh and made His dwelling among us.

02:22.726 --> 02:31.979
We have seen His glory, the glory of the one and only Son who came from the Father full of grace and truth.

02:33.201 --> 02:34.002
The Word of the Lord.

02:38.530 --> 02:45.017
Now, Christmas is the time of the year in which we, as a church, observe and think about the birth of Jesus.

02:45.958 --> 02:50.042
Lent is the time in which we think about the meaning of the death of Jesus.

02:50.102 --> 03:03.095
And traditionally in the church year, the season between Christmas and Lent, not as well known as season, but has got a name, it's called Epiphany.

03:03.996 --> 03:05.778
And Epiphany means,

03:06.050 --> 03:12.359
looking not at the birth of Jesus or the death of Jesus, but at the life of Jesus, what he said, what he did.

03:12.439 --> 03:14.502
And you can't really understand the real Jesus.

03:14.963 --> 03:20.070
If you only look at his birth and his death, you must also look at his words and his deeds during his life.

03:20.191 --> 03:22.454
And that's what we're going to do for the next two months.

03:23.255 --> 03:33.490
And we're going to take one particular gospel, the Gospel of John, and we're going to look at the words and deeds of Jesus in his life between his birth and his death.

03:34.242 --> 03:54.871
Now we start today with John chapter one, the prologue, one of the most rich and famous parts of the Bible, and in some ways it takes pressure off a preacher because preachers always feel like I've gotta give the people, I gotta pull out all the great stuff that's in this text, but this is one of those times in which there's too much great stuff to pull out, I couldn't possibly get it all.

03:54.891 --> 04:02.962
And so I would just like to give you a top level view of it by just outlining it and looking at the three main parts, and therefore the three main points,

04:03.586 --> 04:10.597
Look at verses 1 to 4 is about a claim, a radical, amazing claim.

04:11.538 --> 04:16.005
Verses 5 to 11 is about the rejection of that claim.

04:17.468 --> 04:25.340
But then verses 12 to 14 is the answer to the objections to the claim.

04:25.360 --> 04:31.890
So you have the claim, you have the rejection of the claim, and we have the answers to the objections to and the rejection of the claim.

04:32.386 --> 04:34.288
and let's just walk through it like that.

04:34.989 --> 04:43.320
First of all, the first four verses, very famous, constitute a claim, and it's a claim about the word.

04:44.161 --> 04:45.943
There's five things we're told about the word.

04:47.865 --> 04:52.992
First of all, the word is a person, personal, notice he, the word he.

04:53.392 --> 04:57.858
Secondly, the word was divine, the word was God.

04:58.519 --> 05:01.202
Thirdly, we're not just talking about a divine-ish,

05:01.762 --> 05:05.726
kind of person, but this is a person who has never created.

05:05.766 --> 05:17.998
He's not got a beginning because it says, through him all things were made without him, nothing was made that has been made, which means everything that has a beginning found a beginning in him, which means he's without beginning.

05:20.020 --> 05:24.565
So we have a person, it's a divine person, it's an uncreated divine person.

05:25.105 --> 05:29.810
The source of all life in him was life, not just

05:30.050 --> 05:31.412
He got life or has life.

05:31.832 --> 05:32.694
In him was life.

05:32.894 --> 05:33.995
All life comes from him.

05:34.536 --> 05:40.865
And last thing we learned is all the way at the bottom, for actually in verse 14, it becomes very clear that this is Jesus Christ.

05:42.086 --> 05:47.734
The word became flesh and dwell among us and we beheld His glory.

05:48.835 --> 05:56.626
Now, we could obviously spend five hours, five days, five weeks, maybe five years, taking each of those five claims and pulling them out.

05:56.926 --> 05:59.730
But what's really significant is the word word.

06:00.162 --> 06:10.434
is the fact that John uses this very interesting and unusual way of describing Jesus Christ because he says, in the beginning, was the word.

06:10.474 --> 06:11.275
Jesus is the word.

06:11.956 --> 06:17.042
And because he wrote in Greek, the Greek word that he used here was logos.

06:18.584 --> 06:19.905
In the beginning was the logos.

06:19.965 --> 06:21.968
Jesus Christ was the logos.

06:22.008 --> 06:23.249
The logos became flesh.

06:24.331 --> 06:27.154
Now, John deliberately used a word here

06:27.490 --> 06:34.339
that had an enormous amount of freight, enormous amount of cultural, linguistic, and philosophical freight.

06:34.359 --> 06:42.169
He deliberately used it, and the only way we're gonna understand what it means and why he used it and what a radical claim this is if we get some background.

06:42.209 --> 06:48.036
Now you have to start with the Greek philosophers, because the Greek philosophers came up with this idea of a logos.

06:49.057 --> 06:52.161
They looked at nature, and you know what they saw?

06:52.201 --> 06:55.986
They saw balance, they saw harmony,

06:56.450 --> 07:05.001
They saw an order to nature and they posited that there was a spiritual cosmic principle of order behind it.

07:06.483 --> 07:07.825
So here's one philosophy book.

07:08.806 --> 07:17.778
It says, the logos for the Greeks, this is the philosophy book, was the impersonal harmonious divine structure of the cosmos as a whole.

07:18.306 --> 07:23.373
So behind the order and the balance of nature was the logos.

07:23.393 --> 07:25.896
And the word logos, of course, didn't just mean word.

07:25.956 --> 07:29.821
It has a broader semantic range than our word word.

07:30.602 --> 07:35.388
Logos means purpose or reason, logic, reason for life.

07:36.870 --> 07:42.738
In other words, when they said we believe the universe has a logos, that means that there's an absolute truth

07:43.074 --> 07:45.037
There's a reason for its existence.

07:45.097 --> 07:47.540
There's a meaning to things, a purpose to things.

07:47.560 --> 07:49.763
Now, I think at the gist of this, this is pretty high.

07:49.783 --> 07:51.666
Are you getting kind of philosophical nosebleed?

07:51.686 --> 07:53.088
I know I've got you up here.

07:53.108 --> 07:57.814
Okay, to get to the gist of this, I got to talk about our space heaters in our apartment.

07:59.276 --> 08:04.483
You know, Local Law 11, every so often they've got to do brickwork on the front of our building.

08:04.543 --> 08:06.366
So our building is going through Local Law 11.

08:06.386 --> 08:09.170
You've got these guys going up and down and knocking the bricks out and all that.

08:09.230 --> 08:12.434
And during the day, we are not allowed to turn our heaters on.

08:13.122 --> 08:14.524
because it blows out on the guy.

08:14.604 --> 08:18.250
So I don't know if any of you have looked at the thermometer recently.

08:18.290 --> 08:19.151
That can be a problem.

08:19.211 --> 08:22.556
So the building gives us space heaters.

08:24.298 --> 08:26.862
Now, the space heaters always come with a set of directions.

08:26.922 --> 08:29.526
And it's very important to read the directions because you know what's in the directions?

08:31.489 --> 08:35.034
The logos of the space heater.

08:35.996 --> 08:40.242
The design of the space heater means that there's certain ways in which

08:40.866 --> 08:44.049
You need to use the space here.

08:44.110 --> 08:45.411
It was built in such a way.

08:45.811 --> 08:48.174
You must plug it into these sources, not these sources.

08:49.115 --> 08:51.458
You must put it over here, not over here.

08:51.518 --> 08:53.780
In other words, you have to use it.

08:53.820 --> 08:59.026
Your use must be aligned with its design, with its reason for existence.

08:59.046 --> 09:00.187
It has to be aligned.

09:00.207 --> 09:05.273
Your use has to be aligned with the things that it was designed to do, its reason for existence.

09:05.793 --> 09:10.098
And if you do not use it in alignment with its logos,

09:10.690 --> 09:14.394
At best, you will not get the value out of it.

09:14.535 --> 09:16.717
At worst, you will burn down your place.

09:16.737 --> 09:17.518
You will be a disaster.

09:18.379 --> 09:19.441
Now, here's what the Greek said.

09:19.561 --> 09:21.944
What if the universe is a logos?

09:23.586 --> 09:24.987
What if life has a logos?

09:25.047 --> 09:32.657
What if there is a divine kind of order or structure, a kind of spiritual cosmic structure behind the universe?

09:33.297 --> 09:40.466
And that would mean that if we got our lives in alignment to it, if we aligned with that, our lives would go well.

09:40.898 --> 09:52.297
And if we didn't align with the way things really are, if we didn't align with the logos, the reason for life of the universe, we would experience it the least.

09:52.898 --> 09:55.142
I mean, at best, it would be a lack of contentment at worst.

09:55.162 --> 09:56.163
We might burn our lives down.

09:59.228 --> 10:00.090
And so that's what they did.

10:00.290 --> 10:02.374
What they said is that's what you have to do.

10:02.995 --> 10:05.639
You figure out what that logos is and then you align with it.

10:05.699 --> 10:07.442
Now, of course, the problem was,

10:08.130 --> 10:12.416
Yes, it makes sense to say, I want my life to be aligned with ultimate reality.

10:13.077 --> 10:18.365
I want my life to be aligned with the fabric of the universe, so I'm living along the grain of the universe as it were.

10:18.766 --> 10:22.732
It makes perfect sense, except nobody could completely agree on what it was.

10:23.753 --> 10:27.119
Stoics, now by the word you right away know what I'm going to say.

10:27.519 --> 10:34.770
The Greek Stoics believed that what it meant to align your life with the logos was to just accept everything that happened.

10:36.130 --> 10:37.452
You see, here's nature.

10:37.793 --> 10:43.101
Whatever happens in nature is all right, and therefore you align with it in the Stoics, man, you accept everything.

10:43.581 --> 10:44.222
Stiff up her lip.

10:44.623 --> 10:47.127
Suffering, death, don't let it get to you.

10:48.108 --> 10:54.478
See, that's one way to have a happy life is you get absolutely aligned with the universe and what they meant by that was everything.

10:55.720 --> 10:58.184
Now, you had the Epicureans, you had a lot of other different approaches.

10:58.224 --> 10:59.165
I said, no, no, no, no.

10:59.185 --> 11:04.914
What it means to align with the universe is you just live to make this world a better place for the people who are coming later.

11:05.026 --> 11:06.268
I mean, you live unselfishly.

11:07.169 --> 11:09.834
The Epicurean said, no, no, no, you live selfishly.

11:09.854 --> 11:13.400
They said, the meaning of life is to find what makes you happy and do it.

11:14.221 --> 11:15.783
So people had these different approaches.

11:16.124 --> 11:18.688
You have to align with it and then the earthquake.

11:19.990 --> 11:24.397
It was an earthquake in history because along comes John.

11:25.479 --> 11:27.282
And John says, oh, there is a logos.

11:27.682 --> 11:29.504
But it's not like anything you ever thought.

11:29.564 --> 11:30.766
You're looking for principles.

11:30.786 --> 11:32.147
You're looking for abstractions.

11:32.628 --> 11:34.130
You're looking for books of rules.

11:34.650 --> 11:35.752
He says, there is a logos.

11:36.773 --> 11:39.536
And it is the thing we are to live for.

11:39.596 --> 11:43.681
And the logos is our source of our design.

11:44.362 --> 11:47.146
But it's a person, not a principle.

11:48.487 --> 11:52.732
This history book I was reading, a history philosophy book, says this.

11:54.134 --> 11:56.497
This is written by a French philosophy professor, not a Christian.

11:56.517 --> 11:57.458
He says this.

11:57.602 --> 11:59.504
I'll start with the quote I already gave you.

12:00.124 --> 12:04.969
The logos for the Greeks was the impersonal harmonious divine structure of the cosmos as a whole.

12:06.971 --> 12:22.365
But to the horror of the Greeks, Christians maintain that the logos, in other words, the cosmic principle, was not the harmonious order of the world, but was a single unique personality, one outstanding individual, namely Christ.

12:23.667 --> 12:27.250
Not a principle, but an actual person.

12:28.194 --> 12:44.033
If the heart of the universe was not impersonal as the Greeks and Eastern religions believe, but a person, it meant that there was now an unprecedented emphasis on the idea and importance of love in human life.

12:45.215 --> 12:45.836
But there's more.

12:46.096 --> 12:54.226
By resting its case upon a definition of the human person and an unprecedented idea of love, Christianity was to have an incalculable effect upon the history of ideas.

12:54.498 --> 13:03.469
To give one example, it's quite clear that without this Christian re-evaluation of the human person, the philosophy of human rights to which we subscribe today would never have established itself.

13:04.090 --> 13:04.831
It's absolutely right.

13:05.672 --> 13:09.656
This philosophy professor is not a Christian, by the way, goes on and many others are just the same thing.

13:10.057 --> 13:14.883
If you believe that the universe is essentially impersonal, then people don't really matter.

13:15.484 --> 13:23.273
But if you say the meaning of the universe is essentially personal, it comes from a person, a creator, then persons matter, and everyone has rights and dignity.

13:23.313 --> 13:24.114
But here's the point.

13:26.082 --> 13:26.803
Here's the point.

13:28.225 --> 13:38.598
If you believe that the meaning of life, the reason for life, the logos is basically an abstract principle, then how do you align with that?

13:39.079 --> 13:43.805
Only through, you have to be smart because you have to do philosophical contemplation to figure out what it is.

13:45.467 --> 13:48.771
Or you have to be scientific and you have to check out the order of nature.

13:49.772 --> 13:52.716
And you've got to be strong because you've got to align with it and you've got to be brilliant.

13:52.736 --> 13:54.418
You've got to be self-controlled.

13:55.170 --> 13:56.492
How elitist is that?

13:57.933 --> 13:58.935
What about the rest of us?

13:59.776 --> 14:01.698
But along comes Christianity and says, no, no.

14:02.879 --> 14:03.700
There is a logos.

14:04.722 --> 14:08.026
Life is not a tale told by an idiot full of sound and fury signifying nothing.

14:08.746 --> 14:12.231
There is a meaning to life, but do you want to align with the ultimate reality?

14:12.431 --> 14:18.258
You have to have a relationship with a person, your author, your creator, the progenitor of us all.

14:20.002 --> 14:23.986
and by having a personal relationship of love with him, you are aligned with the universe.

14:24.006 --> 14:31.214
That's revolutionary, not only changed human thought, but of course, it swept the old Roman Empire, and that was the claim.

14:31.474 --> 14:32.796
Do you see how revolutionary it was?

14:32.936 --> 14:46.130
Now, having said that, as great as that claim is, and as amazing as that claim is, and as much as it has actually left a permanent imprint on history, Western civilization, because of Christianity, will always have a higher regard for persons.

14:46.850 --> 14:51.595
then all other kinds of worldviews or background civilizations.

14:51.695 --> 14:57.462
But the second part of this passage says that in spite of all that, there has been widespread rejection of this claim.

14:59.464 --> 15:11.057
In spite of all that, verses 5 to 11 says, there's been widespread rejection of the idea that Jesus Christ is the logos, that he's the meaning of life, that he's the heart of reality that we have to know.

15:12.879 --> 15:15.442
And of course, this section right here

15:16.034 --> 15:16.875
talks about that.

15:16.975 --> 15:20.299
It says, the true light that gives light to everyone was coming into the world.

15:20.319 --> 15:21.381
He was in the world.

15:22.001 --> 15:24.524
And though the world was made through him, the world did not recognize him.

15:25.386 --> 15:27.849
He came to that which was his own, but his own did not receive him.

15:27.909 --> 15:35.458
So this middle section is about the fact that by and large, there has been rejection, a wise red rejection of the claim that Jesus is the logos.

15:35.959 --> 15:42.066
But to understand that rejection, we need to take a look at one really interesting verse that some of you, if you're

15:42.370 --> 15:47.876
familiar with this passage, realize often gets translated in different ways depending on the translation.

15:48.918 --> 15:53.883
It says verses 5, the light shines in the darkness, and what does it say here?

15:55.225 --> 15:56.546
And the darkness has not overcome it.

15:58.589 --> 16:04.015
But you know there are other translations that say the darkness has not understood it.

16:05.557 --> 16:10.162
The old King James Bible says the light shines in the darkness

16:11.106 --> 16:14.991
but the darkness comprehendeth it not.

16:15.011 --> 16:28.911
And actually, one of you, you might be here, we read this during lessons and carols, and one of you in the choir actually came up to me afterwards and said, wait a minute, this morning it was read and said the darkness is not overcome it, but I thought it was the darkness that's not understood it.

16:29.672 --> 16:36.722
Now, the reason is because the word that John uses here again very deliberately is a word that

16:36.866 --> 16:37.707
is ambiguous.

16:37.767 --> 16:44.056
In fact, Don Carson, friend of mine, who's written a commentary on the book of John, says about this verse in this word.

16:44.396 --> 16:47.801
He says, this is a masterpiece of planned ambiguity.

16:49.724 --> 16:56.273
It's a masterpiece of planned ambiguity because the same word can mean overcome and understand.

16:57.054 --> 16:59.838
So you can either fail to overcome something or fail to understand something.

17:00.118 --> 17:01.740
You say, well, they don't seem to be related.

17:01.761 --> 17:03.363
Well, think of the word master for a minute.

17:04.164 --> 17:05.746
What does it mean to master something?

17:06.082 --> 17:10.127
to master something might mean to overpower it, but it also can mean to what?

17:10.508 --> 17:14.553
To master something, to get it, to figure it out.

17:17.577 --> 17:27.129
And I would like you to think for a minute with me what this means is it's the reason it's planned ambiguity is it means there's two different ways at least of rejecting Jesus Christ.

17:28.050 --> 17:32.736
One is to be overtly hostile to him and the other is just to not understand him.

17:32.756 --> 17:33.938
Either way you've rejected him.

17:35.010 --> 17:38.313
is to be overtly hostile or just to not comprehend or get him.

17:38.373 --> 17:40.916
Think maybe you do, but you don't.

17:40.936 --> 17:44.539
Let's take a look at those two.

17:44.559 --> 17:47.842
Jesus was the most influential man to ever walk the earth.

17:48.443 --> 17:53.288
And his story has been told through books, movies, and articles in hundreds of different ways.

17:53.828 --> 17:55.410
Can anything more be said about him?

