18:47.074 --> 18:58.471
First of all, of course, those of us who live in a place like New York City, there's lots of people who just simply don't like, they're just hostile to the idea that Christianity is the truth or that Jesus Christ is the absolute truth behind the universe.

18:59.753 --> 19:04.921
And even to the idea that there is an absolute truth, even to the idea that there is a logos.

19:05.943 --> 19:13.234
So some people are trying to overcome that, that is to say, they're hostile to the idea that there even is absolute truth.

19:14.786 --> 19:22.279
Christian Smith is a sociologist who has studied the religious, moral, and spiritual lives of young adults who live in America.

19:22.519 --> 19:23.440
Very interesting books.

19:24.763 --> 19:31.314
One of the books is called, pardon me, Souls in Transition, and one is called Lost in Transition.

19:31.334 --> 19:34.218
There's another book on teenagers called Soul Searching.

19:35.200 --> 19:41.170
Now, what he says is by talking to thousands and thousands of young adults about their moral views,

19:41.314 --> 19:45.600
He comes to the conclusion that their moral views have three characteristics.

19:45.640 --> 19:45.860
Ready?

19:46.541 --> 19:47.382
Three characteristics.

19:48.544 --> 19:49.045
Listen to this.

19:49.786 --> 19:52.129
First of all, they have very strong moral feelings.

19:54.152 --> 20:06.309
Young adults have very strong moral feelings, very much against injustice, against violation of rights, against ever treating anyone without fairness, against exploitation of the poor, not caring for the poor.

20:07.711 --> 20:09.253
So first of all, they have very strong moral feelings.

20:09.313 --> 20:10.034
Number two,

20:11.458 --> 20:14.562
Secondly, they're moral relativists, okay?

20:15.443 --> 20:20.751
They will say over and over again that no one has the right to tell somebody else what's right or wrong for them.

20:22.313 --> 20:24.236
There's two aspects to that moral relativism.

20:24.917 --> 20:40.498
They would say that morality is person specific and culturally relative, not that they would use those terms as the sociologist terms, but to say person specific is to say everyone has the right to determine what is right or wrong for them and you don't have the right to tell somebody else what's right or wrong for them.

20:40.930 --> 20:46.477
Culturally relative is that every culture has its own set of more ways and ethics, every culture.

20:46.517 --> 20:55.489
And your culture should not be telling their culture that your culture is superior to theirs, that their cultural values are superior to your cultural values.

20:55.509 --> 20:58.173
So first of all, they have strong moral feelings.

20:58.253 --> 21:01.798
Secondly, they're moral relativists.

21:01.818 --> 21:04.381
And thirdly, they believe that morality is self-evident.

21:05.903 --> 21:07.986
Because if you ask a younger American,

21:08.706 --> 21:09.667
Why is that wrong?

21:09.687 --> 21:10.568
You feel that that's wrong.

21:11.269 --> 21:11.950
Why is that wrong?

21:11.970 --> 21:13.031
They'll say, well, everybody knows it.

21:14.854 --> 21:16.556
Well, what are the reasons you believe that's wrong?

21:16.576 --> 21:18.218
Well, it's just people know that.

21:18.358 --> 21:18.899
Everybody knows it.

21:18.919 --> 21:19.840
You just recognize it.

21:22.163 --> 21:24.566
Now, the sociologists took a look at these three things.

21:25.127 --> 21:26.088
And here's what they conclude.

21:27.590 --> 21:30.914
First of all, they conclude that this is incredibly incoherent.

21:32.957 --> 21:34.098
And you know the way it comes out?

21:34.178 --> 21:43.129
They usually, they'll give a younger, listen, some of you, some of you are and some of you aren't in this category of younger adults who live in America.

21:43.149 --> 21:51.339
But one of the questions they'll say is this, hey, do you know about this country, this culture over here, where the husbands won't even let the wise drive?

21:52.641 --> 21:54.663
Women aren't even allowed to have a driver's license?

21:55.965 --> 22:01.411
And do you know about this other country over here where husbands make women can't do this and they can't do that?

22:01.712 --> 22:02.633
Do you think that's right or wrong?

22:02.653 --> 22:03.474
It's wrong!

22:03.650 --> 22:04.391
Why is it wrong?

22:05.031 --> 22:05.812
That's their culture.

22:05.832 --> 22:07.534
Are you saying your culture is better than their culture?

22:09.716 --> 22:10.477
Total's crickets.

22:12.499 --> 22:13.740
And here's why it's incoherent.

22:14.981 --> 22:15.962
They have strong moral feelings.

22:15.982 --> 22:18.485
They have absolutely no basis for a program of justice.

22:18.505 --> 22:21.988
They have no basis on which they can say to somebody you're doing wrong.

22:23.190 --> 22:26.353
They have strong moral feelings, but have no way of carrying out any kind of program.

22:26.393 --> 22:27.354
It's totally incoherent.

22:29.015 --> 22:31.538
And secondly, they point out, the sociologists say,

22:31.842 --> 22:39.230
that these three views, strong moral feelings, moral relativism, and the idea that morality is self-evident, which it isn't, by the way.

22:40.912 --> 22:42.694
They already disagree, it's not going to be self-evident.

22:44.155 --> 22:55.988
The thirdly, they say it's not only incoherent, it's inconsistent, and they point out that younger Americans, even though they feel very strongly, we shouldn't hurt the poor, we should care for the poor, are unbelievably consumeristic and selfish with the way they spend money on themselves.

22:58.851 --> 22:59.612
Well, that's a problem.

23:00.933 --> 23:01.714
Isn't that a problem?

23:02.018 --> 23:03.039
There's no absolute truth.

23:03.059 --> 23:05.682
That leads to being inconsistent and incoherent.

23:08.025 --> 23:08.546
So what do we do?

23:09.226 --> 23:10.548
Oh, well, we decide there is a logos.

23:10.568 --> 23:11.529
There is absolute truth.

23:12.370 --> 23:13.151
And what do we do?

23:13.331 --> 23:16.274
We say we're going to believe in absolute truth.

23:16.334 --> 23:16.655
Oh, yes.

23:17.055 --> 23:23.443
There are moral absolutes and we're going to accept that and we're going to embrace that and we're going to bring our lives and alignment with that.

23:23.503 --> 23:25.004
We're going to try to be really good persons.

23:26.226 --> 23:28.489
How's that work?

23:28.509 --> 23:29.810
And let me tell you how that works.

23:32.258 --> 23:34.581
Just to say, those are moral absolutes.

23:35.503 --> 23:37.786
There's the logos and I'm gonna live up to it.

23:39.769 --> 23:40.730
It's oppressive.

23:40.750 --> 23:41.912
It's oppressive in two ways.

23:42.572 --> 23:44.435
It leads to oppression in two ways.

23:44.996 --> 23:47.419
Number one, it can either oppress you.

23:47.459 --> 23:54.129
It can crush you because you're trying so hard to live up according to it and you're never gonna get there and you're always hating yourself.

23:54.149 --> 23:55.130
You're always beating yourself up.

23:55.150 --> 23:56.652
I'm just not the person I should be.

23:58.054 --> 24:00.818
That's one way of aligning with the universe but it doesn't work.

24:03.074 --> 24:06.538
So one way it can be oppressive is that you can live up to it and not live up to it.

24:06.598 --> 24:08.681
And so you're oppressed on the inside.

24:08.721 --> 24:10.903
The other bad thing that could happen is you could live up to it.

24:11.624 --> 24:17.071
You might be one of those elite people who actually can set your standards and live up to them.

24:17.171 --> 24:19.313
In which case, you're not oppressed on the inside.

24:19.334 --> 24:20.275
You become an oppressor.

24:22.257 --> 24:23.599
In other words, you become a bigot.

24:23.699 --> 24:24.740
You become self-righteous.

24:24.780 --> 24:25.781
You become a Pharisee.

24:25.821 --> 24:27.684
You become someone who says, look, I'm good.

24:27.724 --> 24:28.424
Why can't you be?

24:29.125 --> 24:29.746
Suck it up.

24:30.530 --> 24:31.691
I've pulled myself together.

24:31.751 --> 24:32.973
I've kept myself out of jail.

24:33.053 --> 24:33.894
I've made a lot of money.

24:34.094 --> 24:34.495
You're poor.

24:34.715 --> 24:35.176
You're in jail.

24:35.196 --> 24:36.097
You're in this life.

24:36.117 --> 24:36.677
What's wrong with you?

24:39.040 --> 24:42.124
So you see, if you say, well, there is no logos.

24:42.144 --> 24:43.065
There's no moral absolutes.

24:43.085 --> 24:43.586
What have you got?

24:43.706 --> 24:45.108
Incoherence and inconsistency.

24:45.588 --> 24:47.571
So all right, I'm going to align myself with the logos.

24:47.591 --> 24:48.291
There is a logo.

24:48.312 --> 24:49.233
So I'm going to align with it.

24:49.553 --> 24:56.061
You have oppression, either oppression on the inside or oppression through you on the outside.

24:58.624 --> 25:00.306
But that's not what Jesus is about.

25:00.386 --> 25:02.168
See, it's one thing to say there is no logos.

25:02.208 --> 25:05.972
Another thing to say, well, there is a logos, but was Jesus about moralism?

25:07.294 --> 25:12.420
See, to say there is no logos as relativism, but to say there is a logos and I'm going to live up to it is moralism.

25:12.500 --> 25:13.301
Is Jesus about that?

25:13.361 --> 25:13.601
No.

25:14.061 --> 25:15.143
And here's where you see it.

25:15.883 --> 25:19.488
Verse 11, he came to that which was his own, but his own did not receive him.

25:20.569 --> 25:23.352
He came to his own, but his own received him not.

25:24.353 --> 25:24.633
Why?

25:25.654 --> 25:26.676
Well, he was Jewish, right?

25:27.677 --> 25:28.818
He went to the Jews.

25:30.114 --> 25:30.915
And they rejected him.

25:30.935 --> 25:31.235
Why?

25:31.276 --> 25:34.420
Because they didn't comprehend him.

25:35.121 --> 25:36.042
They didn't get him.

25:36.182 --> 25:36.502
Why?

25:36.963 --> 25:38.285
Because he did these strange things.

25:38.325 --> 25:40.328
He hung out with prostitutes and with sinners.

25:41.489 --> 25:43.812
And then he said to the Pharisees, and they were very good people.

25:43.852 --> 25:46.396
They were aligned with the absolute truth.

25:47.177 --> 25:53.084
One place where Jesus looks at the Pharisees and said, the prostitutes and the Hormongers get into heaven before you.

25:56.589 --> 25:57.330
They didn't get them.

25:58.466 --> 26:02.010
Because you see, he's not about, obviously, relativism.

26:02.491 --> 26:03.112
Jesus is not.

26:03.152 --> 26:06.656
If you're a relativist, you've rejected Jesus, but moralism is also to reject Jesus.

26:08.118 --> 26:10.441
It's not to comprehend him, not to understand what he's about.

26:10.461 --> 26:18.150
And before moving on to the last point to show how we get out of this conundrum, may I say something very daring, kind of daring.

26:18.170 --> 26:21.454
It's not like some of you said you haven't ever said this before, but it still feels daring.

26:22.836 --> 26:23.877
Who are his own today?

26:23.897 --> 26:27.602
I mean, if we're talking about Jesus' own,

26:27.938 --> 26:28.579
Who are the own?

26:28.599 --> 26:29.441
Who's his own today?

26:29.481 --> 26:32.126
It's us.

26:32.146 --> 26:32.406
It's us.

26:32.426 --> 26:32.988
It's the church.

26:33.509 --> 26:35.051
It's the people who say we're Christians.

26:36.454 --> 26:39.380
To what degree do we not get Jesus?

26:39.440 --> 26:41.363
To what degree do we not comprehend Him?

26:42.526 --> 26:46.994
To what degree do we fall into moralism as opposed to understanding the gospel?

26:48.226 --> 26:52.971
To what degree are we places that, well, we believe in absolute truth, but we are vehicles for oppression.

26:52.991 --> 26:54.313
That is oppression inside.

26:54.713 --> 26:57.296
People always feeling guilty and like I can never live up.

26:57.316 --> 26:58.037
We're outside.

27:01.280 --> 27:02.381
Okay, now see the problem?

27:03.122 --> 27:07.707
Here's the solution, but let me just draw one, just for 90 seconds, what the problem is.

27:08.568 --> 27:15.996
On the one hand, you have one wave rejecting this claim, relativism, but the other wave rejecting is moralism, and we are stuck, and I'll tell you why.

27:16.016 --> 27:17.618
Our culture has,

27:18.338 --> 27:19.460
rejected moralism.

27:20.501 --> 27:21.182
We don't like it.

27:21.663 --> 27:23.706
We don't like people saying they have the absolute truth.

27:23.766 --> 27:24.547
We've rejected that.

27:24.928 --> 27:35.644
And to put it in a little cultural context, let me just, those of you who are my age, those of you who, you know, your hair's not the same colors it used to be, we grew up, who are the bad people?

27:35.684 --> 27:37.968
If you grew up in America, who are the bad people?

27:39.050 --> 27:40.291
Who are the people trying to blow us up?

27:41.894 --> 27:43.256
Communists, right?

27:44.017 --> 27:45.800
And who are the communists?

27:45.820 --> 27:47.282
They didn't believe in God.

27:48.578 --> 27:52.943
All right, so religious people were the good people and the people who didn't believe in God were the bad people.

27:52.983 --> 27:55.647
And that's what we grew up with.

27:55.667 --> 28:04.357
Okay, but a lot of you, whose life looks like your hair is what it was when you were born, you grew up with a very, very different situation.

28:04.377 --> 28:05.839
Who are the people trying to blow us up now?

28:07.541 --> 28:08.622
Religious fanatics.

28:10.344 --> 28:11.546
People who think they have the truth.

28:12.507 --> 28:15.090
And see, if you grew up with that shadow,

28:15.170 --> 28:18.695
You don't like religion or you're scared of it or anybody who believes too much.

28:20.498 --> 28:28.088
But we've just said, if you say there is no logos, everybody has to decide what is right or wrong for you.

28:28.108 --> 28:29.270
Do you realize where that is?

28:30.051 --> 28:34.057
Incoherence and inconsistency and no basis for a program of justice.

28:34.117 --> 28:35.058
It's a problem.

28:36.130 --> 28:38.513
But what's the other problem, of course, is moralism.

28:38.654 --> 28:40.156
So is there a way through?

28:40.436 --> 28:41.317
Is there a way forward?

28:41.898 --> 28:43.460
Is there a way to solve this problem?

28:43.500 --> 28:57.199
Yes, there has been for 2,000 years, it's called the Gospel of Jesus Christ, and it is beautifully, beautifully put in these last three verses, memorably, famously, as good of three verses as you'd ever want to explain the gospel.

28:59.182 --> 29:04.850
To all who did receive him, who believed in his name, he gave right to become children of God, children born,

29:04.994 --> 29:14.868
not of natural descent, nor of human decision, or of a husband's will, but born of God, for the word became flesh and made his dwelling among us, and we have seen his glory.

29:16.229 --> 29:20.655
Glory of the one and only son who came from the Father full of grace and truth.

29:21.597 --> 29:27.325
Okay, first of all, let's just unpack this briefly, but carefully.

29:28.106 --> 29:30.008
First of all, it says, not everybody's a child of God.

29:30.189 --> 29:31.250
It has to be received.

29:32.898 --> 29:38.124
See, this pushes against the popular idea that all human beings are God's children.

29:38.204 --> 29:40.727
Now, the Bible says in one sense that's true.

29:41.908 --> 29:45.452
Paul says in Acts 17, we are his offspring.

29:45.492 --> 29:47.835
In fact, he's talking to Greek philosophers, interestingly enough.

29:49.016 --> 29:50.238
Paul talks to the Greek philosophers.

29:50.258 --> 29:55.764
To the Stoics, the Epicureans, the people who were looking for the logos and all, he says, we are his offspring.

29:56.505 --> 30:01.010
And in a sense, because God created us, yes, just like, you know, Henry Ford is the

30:01.762 --> 30:08.428
Father of the Model T. And God is our father in a sense that he's our creator and he's produces.

30:09.189 --> 30:16.916
But the Bible in general does not say that God is your father just because you've been born.

30:18.077 --> 30:26.345
Because the idea of having a relationship of child, the father, son, or daughter, the father is so special in the Bible, it's a gift, how so?

30:27.726 --> 30:31.730
Well, if you are an employee and you have a boss,

30:32.354 --> 30:35.659
and you misbehave what happens.

30:35.679 --> 30:41.527
The more you misbehave, the more your boss' boss' regard for you goes down and eventually you lose your job.

30:41.547 --> 30:42.028
You know why?

30:42.088 --> 30:47.916
Because your job, your relationship with your boss is based on your performance and a cost-benefit analysis, right?

30:49.738 --> 31:00.914
I mean, not that your boss might not be sympathetic, but if you keep misbehaving, his regard goes down, her regard goes down for you and eventually you lose your job because your relationship is based on your performance and cost-benefit.

31:01.186 --> 31:07.936
But if you're a good father and you've got some children and one of them really starts to misbehave what happens.

31:09.899 --> 31:11.842
Your father's heart is more engaged.

31:13.585 --> 31:15.728
Your father love is more intensified.

31:15.749 --> 31:16.269
You know why?

31:16.309 --> 31:20.255
Because your relationship between a child and a father is not based on performance.

31:20.296 --> 31:21.598
It's not a consumer relationship.

31:21.998 --> 31:22.920
It's not cost-benefit.

31:23.220 --> 31:24.662
It is a covenant relationship.

31:24.702 --> 31:29.650
It is based on unconditional faithfulness and commitment.

31:32.162 --> 31:33.103
And what does that mean?

31:38.128 --> 31:42.612
If you don't have an appointment with the president of the United States and you try to get in to see him, you'll be stopped.

31:44.254 --> 31:50.840
If you don't have an appointment with the president of the United States and you start running toward him, you'll be shot.

31:52.161 --> 31:59.789
In fact, even if you do have an appointment with the president of the United States and you start running toward him, you'll probably be shot.

31:59.809 --> 32:01.010
But if he's your daddy,

32:01.250 --> 32:03.072
Because you're his little boy, you're his little girl.

32:03.712 --> 32:04.433
You go right in.

32:05.594 --> 32:06.655
You don't have to have credentials.

32:06.675 --> 32:08.437
You don't have to be worth the price at its time.

32:08.497 --> 32:16.205
Is it possible to have a relationship like that with God, the author of the universe?

32:18.908 --> 32:21.070
Yes, a relationship is on grace.

32:21.130 --> 32:21.370
Why?

32:21.390 --> 32:22.011
How could that be?

32:22.051 --> 32:22.552
Here's how.

32:23.573 --> 32:27.036
The word became flesh and dwelt among us.

32:27.096 --> 32:28.277
And again, it's amazing.

32:28.417 --> 32:28.978
John,

32:29.570 --> 32:37.261
When he's writing in Greek, he's being so careful because the word that's there is, it says, the word became flesh and tabernacled among us.

32:39.484 --> 32:40.246
Tabernacled.

32:41.848 --> 32:42.929
What was the tabernacled?

32:42.950 --> 32:43.711
What was the temple?

32:44.071 --> 32:44.792
Do you know what it was?

32:46.354 --> 32:49.359
All around the world, there have always been temples.

32:49.960 --> 32:50.420
Do you know why?

32:51.562 --> 32:57.010
Because all human beings instinctively sense that if there is a God, there's a gap.

32:59.330 --> 33:05.256
If there is a God, God is great and we're small, God is perfect and we're flawed.

33:05.716 --> 33:08.880
If there is a God, there's a gap and temples replaces to bridge the gap.

33:09.660 --> 33:17.629
You had offerings and you had sacrifices and you atoned for sin and you, you sought to do everything you could to bridge the gap.

33:17.649 --> 33:19.711
You had priests who did it full time for you.

33:20.852 --> 33:26.898
But now we're told Jesus becomes the tabernacle, Jesus becomes the temple.

33:28.002 --> 33:34.669
He is the ultimate priest because he's laid down the ultimate sacrifice when he went to the cross, he died for our sins, and that means he's the temple.

33:34.709 --> 33:36.010
He gets rid of the need for temples.

33:39.954 --> 33:43.337
And we can become children by grace.

33:44.238 --> 33:47.862
Now, that is exactly what you need.

33:47.882 --> 33:48.503
You know what that is?

33:50.985 --> 33:55.730
We can't live without absolutes, but we can't have an oppressive absolute

33:55.906 --> 33:58.509
We need a non-oppressive absolute, okay, everybody?

33:59.330 --> 34:00.651
Write this down, memorize this.

34:01.372 --> 34:03.474
We need a non-oppressive absolute, and here it is.

34:04.115 --> 34:05.917
A man dying on the cross for your sins.

34:07.138 --> 34:09.561
A God of strength becoming weak and flesh.

34:12.404 --> 34:21.213
A man with life going to the cross and losing his life, being the ultimate sacrifice, tabernacleing, becoming our temple.

34:22.134 --> 34:25.458
And if you see a man dying for his enemies, sacrificing his life

34:25.538 --> 34:26.520
forgiving his enemies.

34:27.822 --> 34:30.005
That can't make you into an oppressor.

34:30.947 --> 34:32.870
On the one hand, that means I'm saved by grace.

34:32.910 --> 34:34.152
That won't crush me on the inside.

34:34.192 --> 34:40.682
On the other hand, if I am saved by grace, it's only because I don't deserve it and I can't feel superior to anybody else, so that doesn't make me a oppressor to anyone else.

34:40.983 --> 34:43.186
You say, but haven't Christians been oppressors in the past?

34:43.226 --> 34:45.029
Yes, only if they didn't comprehend it.

34:46.251 --> 34:48.515
See, only if they didn't understand it.

34:50.338 --> 34:51.279
Only if they didn't get it.

34:51.920 --> 34:52.882
And the ones who did.

34:53.538 --> 34:56.162
the early Christians invented orphanages, invented hospitals.

34:56.202 --> 34:57.204
They didn't exist before.

34:57.925 --> 34:59.467
They stopped the infanticide of girls.

34:59.507 --> 35:00.449
They changed history.

35:02.712 --> 35:07.139
Now you, you comprehended.

35:09.603 --> 35:21.842
Get a relationship with the heart of reality, a love relationship based on grace, and then go out and take your part

35:22.530 --> 35:25.994
in continuing to change history until he comes again.

35:26.674 --> 35:27.175
Let's pray.

35:27.956 --> 35:35.624
Our Father, we thank you that you have given us a wonderful glimpse of who Jesus Christ is.

35:35.644 --> 35:39.648
And we ask that you would help us to apply this to our lives.

35:39.688 --> 35:41.850
We want to be agents out there in the world.

35:41.870 --> 35:49.458
The world needs people who not only can help them find God and connect to you through Jesus Christ,

35:49.826 --> 35:54.133
But even if they don't believe the gospel, they need people around who have been changed by the gospel.

35:55.074 --> 36:00.784
People who are not oppressors, who pour themselves out even for their enemies and opponents the way your son Jesus did.

36:01.605 --> 36:04.530
Oh Father, please change us with the gospel.

36:05.411 --> 36:08.737
So the people can see that you sent your son.

36:10.059 --> 36:14.426
Help us to apply this to our lives, to the Holy Spirit in Jesus' name we pray.

36:14.446 --> 36:14.546
Amen.

36:19.458 --> 36:22.321
Thanks for listening to Tim Keller on the Gospel and Life podcast.

36:22.801 --> 36:31.490
If you'd like to see more people encouraged by the Gospel-centered teaching and resources of this ministry, we invite you to consider becoming a Gospel and Life monthly partner.

36:32.010 --> 36:37.035
Your partnership connects people all over the world with the life-giving power of Christ's love.

36:37.476 --> 36:40.579
To learn more, just visit gospelandlife.com slash partner.

36:41.039 --> 36:44.242
That website again is gospelandlife.com slash partner.

36:45.423 --> 36:48.146
Today's sermon was recorded in 2014.

36:48.322 --> 36:57.810
The sermons and talks you hear on the Gospel and Life podcast were recorded between 1989 and 2017, while Dr. Keller was senior pastor at Redeemer Presbyterian Church.

